            <p>New York Apr 5&#47;89<lb/></p>
            <p>Dear Dr&#33;<lb/></p>
            <p>For the month of<lb/> March I can only report a<lb/> steady progress in the well<lb/> defined lines of study.  In<lb/> the Preparatory Departments I<lb/> continued the reading of Genesis<lb/> with &#91;Hebrew&#93; to the end of Cap. XXXI&#44; in<lb/> Grammar we took the verbs with<lb/> ×¤ Guttural&#44; in History to the end<lb/> of the Judgeship of Jephthah&#44; in<lb/> reading at sight to the end of Josh&#45;<lb/>&#45;ua and beginning of review and<lb/> in Psalms to end of Psalm IXI.<lb/>  In the Junior Department I con&#45;<lb/>&#45;tinued the reading and exegesis<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>of Isaiah to the end of Cap. X&#44;<lb/> History through the Maccabean<lb/> uprising and Grammar to the<lb/> norms formed by suffixes.<lb/>  At present my entire exertions<lb/> are devoted to thorough review<lb/> and preparations in all these sub&#45;<lb/>&#45;jects for the public examinations<lb/> in <sic>may</sic>.  On this subject I<lb/> would much like to have your<lb/> instruction so as to know what<lb/> form the public examination and<lb/> celebration shall take.<lb/></p>
            <p>I remain<lb/> With best regards<lb/> Bernard Drachman<lb/></p>
            </body>
    </text>
